## Testing Strategy

### Unit Tests (`test_weight_calibrator.py`)

```python
def test_success_rate_high_success_scenarios():
    """Scenario with 9/10 success should get 0.9 weight."""

def test_keyword_boost_calculation():
    """Keywords from high-success scenarios should get boost."""

def test_minimum_samples_gate():
    """Don't calibrate scenarios with < 5 interventions."""

def test_decay_penalizes_old_data():
    """Old interventions weighted less than recent."""

def test_dry_run_no_persistence():
    """Dry-run should not save weights to disk."""
```

### Integration Tests (`test_router_runtime.py`)

```python
def test_router_routes_with_calibrated_weights():
    """High-success scenarios should rank higher."""

def test_router_fallback_without_calibrator():
    """Router should work without calibrator (baseline)."""
```

### Manual Testing

- Generate test interventions with success/fail mix
- Run `--calibrate-weights --dry-run`
- Verify weights boost high-success scenarios
- Compare routing confidence before/after calibration

---

## Risk & Mitigation

| Risk | Mitigation |
|------|------------|
| Overfitting to small sample | min_samples gate (default 5) |
| Old data skewing weights | Decay function favors recent |
| Weights regressing performance | A/B test before applying |
| DB query slow | Cache weights, rebuild on demand |
| Circular dependency (router → calibrator) | Separate modules, calibrate once at startup |

